121/**
122 * CharacterMovementComponent handles movement logic for the associated Character owner.
123 * It supports various movement modes including: walking, falling, swimming, flying, custom.
124 *
125 * Movement is affected primarily by current Velocity and Acceleration. Acceleration is updated each frame
126 * based on the input vector accumulated thus far (see UPawnMovementComponent::GetPendingInputVector()).
127 *
128 * Networking is fully implemented, with server-client correction and prediction included.
129 *
130 * @see ACharacter, UPawnMovementComponent
131 * @see https://docs.unrealengine.com/latest/INT/Gameplay/Framework/Pawn/Character/
132 */
133

191 /**
192 * A normalized vector representing the direction of gravity for gravity relative movement modes: walking, falling,
193 * and custom movement modes. Gravity direction remaps player input as being within the plane defined by the gravity
194 * direction. Movement simulation values like velocity and acceleration are maintained in their existing world coordinate
195 * space but are transformed internally as gravity relative (for instance moving forward up a vertical wall that gravity is
196 * defined to be perpendicular to and jump "up" from that wall). If ShouldRemainVertical() is true the character's capsule
197 * will be oriented to align with the gravity direction.
198 */
199 UPROPERTY(Category="Character Movement: Gravity", VisibleAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly, meta = (AllowPrivateAccess = true))

218 /**
219 * Actor's current movement mode (walking, falling, etc).
220 * - walking: Walking on a surface, under the effects of friction, and able to "step up" barriers. Vertical velocity is zero.
221 * - falling: Falling under the effects of gravity, after jumping or walking off the edge of a surface.
222 * - flying: Flying, ignoring the effects of gravity.
223 * - swimming: Swimming through a fluid volume, under the effects of gravity and buoyancy.
224 * - custom: User-defined custom movement mode, including many possible sub-modes.
225 * This is automatically replicated through the Character owner and for client-server movement functions.
226 * @see SetMovementMode(), CustomMovementMode

299 /**
300 * Friction (drag) coefficient applied when braking (whenever Acceleration = 0, or if character is exceeding max speed); actual value used is this multiplied by BrakingFrictionFactor.
301 * When braking, this property allows you to control how much friction is applied when moving across the ground, applying an opposing force that scales with current velocity.
302 * Braking is composed of friction (velocity-dependent drag) and constant deceleration.
303 * This is the current value, used in all movement modes; if this is not desired, override it or bUseSeparateBrakingFriction when movement mode changes.
304 * @note Only used if bUseSeparateBrakingFriction setting is true, otherwise current friction such as GroundFriction is used.
305 * @see bUseSeparateBrakingFriction, BrakingFrictionFactor, GroundFriction, BrakingDecelerationWalking

717 /**
718 * Compute remaining time step given remaining time and current iterations.
719 * The last iteration (limited by MaxSimulationIterations) always returns the remaining time, which may violate MaxSimulationTimeStep.
720 *
721 * @param RemainingTime Remaining time in the tick.
722 * @param Iterations Current iteration of the tick (starting at 1).
723 * @return The remaining time step to use for the next sub-step of iteration.
724 * @see MaxSimulationTimeStep, MaxSimulationIterations
725 */
726 ENGINE_API float GetSimulationTimeStep(float RemainingTime, int32 Iterations) const;

728 /**
729 * Max time delta for each discrete simulation step.
730 * Used primarily in the the more advanced movement modes that break up larger time steps (usually those applying gravity such as falling and walking).
731 * Lowering this value can address issues with fast-moving objects or complex collision scenarios, at the cost of performance.
732 *
733 * WARNING: if (MaxSimulationTimeStep * MaxSimulationIterations) is too low for the min framerate, the last simulation step may exceed MaxSimulationTimeStep to complete the simulation.
734 * @see MaxSimulationIterations
735 */
736 UPROPERTY(Category="Character Movement (General Settings)", EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, AdvancedDisplay, meta=(ClampMin="0.0166", ClampMax="0.50", UIMin="0.0166", UIMax="0.50"))
737 float MaxSimulationTimeStep;
738
739 /**
740 * Max number of iterations used for each discrete simulation step.
741 * Used primarily in the the more advanced movement modes that break up larger time steps (usually those applying gravity such as falling and walking).
742 * Increasing this value can address issues with fast-moving objects or complex collision scenarios, at the cost of performance.
743 *
744 * WARNING: if (MaxSimulationTimeStep * MaxSimulationIterations) is too low for the min framerate, the last simulation step may exceed MaxSimulationTimeStep to complete the simulation.
745 * @see MaxSimulationTimeStep
746 */
747 UPROPERTY(Category="Character Movement (General Settings)", EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite, AdvancedDisplay, meta=(ClampMin="1", ClampMax="25", UIMin="1", UIMax="25"))
748 int32 MaxSimulationIterations;

2066 /**
2067 * Compute distance to the floor from bottom sphere of capsule and store the result in OutFloorResult.
2068 * This distance is the swept distance of the capsule to the first point impacted by the lower hemisphere, or distance from the bottom of the capsule in the case of a line trace.
2069 * This function does not care if collision is disabled on the capsule (unlike FindFloor).
2070 * @see FindFloor
2071 *
2072 * @param CapsuleLocation: Location of the capsule used for the query
2073 * @param LineDistance: If non-zero, max distance to test for a simple line check from the capsule base. Used only if the sweep test fails to find a walkable floor, and only returns a valid result if the impact normal is a walkable normal.
2074 * @param SweepDistance: If non-zero, max distance to use when sweeping a capsule downwards for the test. MUST be greater than or equal to the line distance.

2325 /*
2326 ========================================================================
2327 Here's how player movement prediction, replication and correction works in network games:
2328
2329 Every tick, the TickComponent() function is called. It figures out the acceleration and rotation change for the frame,
2330 and then calls PerformMovement() (for locally controlled Characters), or ReplicateMoveToServer() (if it's a network client).
2331
2332 ReplicateMoveToServer() saves the move (in the PendingMove list), calls PerformMovement(), and then replicates the move
2333 to the server by calling the replicated function ServerMove() - passing the movement parameters, the client's
2334 resultant position, and a timestamp.
2335
2336 ServerMove() is executed on the server. It decodes the movement parameters and causes the appropriate movement
2337 to occur. It then looks at the resulting position and if enough time has passed since the last response, or the
2338 position error is significant enough, the server calls ClientAdjustPosition(), a replicated function.
2339
2340 ClientAdjustPosition() is executed on the client. The client sets its position to the servers version of position,
2341 and sets the bUpdatePosition flag to true.
2342
2343 When TickComponent() is called on the client again, if bUpdatePosition is true, the client will call
2344 ClientUpdatePosition() before calling PerformMovement(). ClientUpdatePosition() replays all the moves in the pending
2345 move list which occurred after the timestamp of the move the server was adjusting.
2346 */
2347
2348 /** Perform local movement and send the move to the server. */
2349 ENGINE_API virtual void ReplicateMoveToServer(float DeltaTime, const FVector& NewAcceleration);
2350
2351 /** If bUpdatePosition is true, then replay any unacked moves. Returns whether any moves were actually replayed. */
2352 ENGINE_API virtual bool ClientUpdatePositionAfterServerUpdate();
2353
2354 /** Call the appropriate replicated ServerMove() function to send a client player move to the server. */
2355 DEPRECATED_CHARACTER_MOVEMENT_RPC(CallServerMove, CallServerMovePacked)

2880FORCEINLINE uint32 UCharacterMovementComponent::PackYawAndPitchTo32(const float Yaw, const float Pitch)
2881{
2882 const uint32 YawShort = FRotator::CompressAxisToShort(Yaw);
2883 const uint32 PitchShort = FRotator::CompressAxisToShort(Pitch);
2884 const uint32 Rotation32 = (YawShort << 16) | PitchShort;
2885 return Rotation32;
2886}
